SQL AND Operator

The SQL AND operator is used in the WHERE clause to filter records based on more than one condition.
A row is returned only when every condition joined by AND evaluates to TRUE.

AND Syntax:
SELECT column1, column2, ...
FROM table_name
WHERE condition1 AND condition2 AND condition3 ...;

Example 1: Simple AND Condition
Select all customers from Spain whose name starts with G:
SELECT *
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Spain' AND CustomerName LIKE 'G%';

What this does:
This query returns rows where both Country is Spain and the customer name begins with G.
When to use it:
Use this when multiple filters must all be satisfied.

Example 2: AND with Numeric Comparison
Select customers from Brazil with CustomerID greater than 50:
SELECT *
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Brazil' AND City = 'Rio de Janeiro' AND CustomerID > 50;

What this does:
This query returns only rows that satisfy all three conditions.
When to use it:
Use this when you need strict filtering across multiple fields.

Example 3: Combining multiple text conditions
Select customers from Mexico in the city México D.F.:
SELECT CustomerName, City, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Mexico' AND City = 'México D.F.';

What this does:
This query returns Mexican customers located in México D.F.
When to use it:
Use this when you need a specific country and city combination.

Example 4: AND with a range and text condition
Select customers from Germany with CustomerID between 1 and 10:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Germany' AND CustomerID BETWEEN 1 AND 10;

What this does:
This query returns German customers whose IDs are within a range.
When to use it:
Use this when you need both a text match and a numeric range.

Example 5: AND with a pattern and numeric filter
Select customers whose name starts with 'A' and whose ID is less than 20:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE CustomerName LIKE 'A%' AND CustomerID < 20;

What this does:
This query returns rows that match a name pattern and a numeric limit.
When to use it:
Use this when you need both pattern matching and numeric filtering.

Example 6: AND with multiple numeric conditions
Select customers with ID greater than 1 and less than or equal to 5:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName
FROM Customers
WHERE CustomerID > 1 AND CustomerID <= 5;

What this does:
This query returns customers with IDs 2 through 5.
When to use it:
Use this to specify a bounded numeric range with AND.

Example 7: AND with a text condition and an alias
Select customers in Sweden and show the country as CountryName:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country AS CountryName
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Sweden' AND City = 'Luleå';

What this does:
This query filters by country and city and renames the output column.
When to use it:
Use this for filtered results with clearer column labels.

Example 8: AND with ORDER BY
Select customers from the UK and order by CustomerName:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, City, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'UK' AND City = 'London'
ORDER BY CustomerName;

What this does:
This query filters UK London customers and sorts them by name.
When to use it:
Use this when you need ordered results for a specific filtered subset.

Example 9: AND with LIMIT
Select the first 2 matching Swedish customers:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Sweden' AND City = 'Luleå'
LIMIT 2;

What this does:
This query returns only the first two rows that match the filter.
When to use it:
Use this to limit the number of matching rows returned.

Example 10: AND in UPDATE and DELETE
Update all Mexican customers in México D.F. to a new city:
UPDATE Customers
SET City = 'Mexico City'
WHERE Country = 'Mexico' AND City = 'México D.F.';

What this does:
This update changes only the filtered rows that match both conditions.
When to use it:
Use this for a precise bulk update on specific records.

Delete all customers in the UK and London:
DELETE FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'UK' AND City = 'London';

What this does:
This delete removes only the rows that meet both country and city criteria.
When to use it:
Use this to delete a narrowly defined subset of rows.

AND vs OR
----------
- AND requires all conditions to be true.
- OR requires any one of the conditions to be true.

Example 11: AND only
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Spain' AND CustomerName LIKE 'G%';

What this does:
This query returns Spanish customers whose names start with G.
When to use it:
Use this when both filters are required.

Example 12: OR only
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Spain' OR Country = 'Mexico';

What this does:
This query returns customers from either Spain or Mexico.
When to use it:
Use this when any one of several values is acceptable.

Example 13: AND combined with OR
Select Spanish customers whose name starts with G or R:
SELECT *
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Spain' AND (CustomerName LIKE 'G%' OR CustomerName LIKE 'R%');

What this does:
This query returns Spanish customers whose name starts with G or R.
When to use it:
Use this to combine strict and flexible conditions.

Why parentheses are important:
Without parentheses, this query changes meaning:
SELECT *
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Spain' AND CustomerName LIKE 'G%' OR CustomerName LIKE 'R%';

What this does:
This query returns Spanish customers starting with G and all customers starting with R.
When to use it:
Use parentheses to enforce the intended logic.

Example 14: AND with multiple OR groups
Select customers from Mexico or the UK whose names start with A:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE (Country = 'Mexico' OR Country = 'UK')
  AND CustomerName LIKE 'A%';

What this does:
This query returns A-names from Mexico or the UK.
When to use it:
Use this when you need a combined group filter and pattern filter.

Example 15: AND with IN and LIKE
Select customers from Germany or Sweden whose names start with B:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country IN ('Germany', 'Sweden')
  AND CustomerName LIKE 'B%';

What this does:
This query returns B-name customers in Germany or Sweden.
When to use it:
Use this to combine a list filter with a pattern filter.

